# 🫀 Heart Attack Prediction & Interactive AI Diagnostics Pipeline

An end-to-end, decoupled clinical diagnostic web application that predicts individual heart disease risk probability using a machine learning soft-voting ensemble model. The application features local and global algorithmic explainability via **SHAP** and **LIME** and includes an integrated medical AI chatbot powered by **LangChain Mistral AI**.

---


## 🚀 Key Features

- **Decoupled Architecture:** Separated high-performance FastAPI Python backend engine from a lightweight, responsive HTML5/CSS3/JavaScript frontend dashboard.
- **Ensemble Machine Learning:** Employs a robust Soft-Voting Classifier combination (including XGBoost, LightGBM, and Random Forest) to output statistical risk percentages.
- **Explainable AI (XAI):**
  - **SHAP Waterfall Plots:** Visualizes global feature importance to show which baseline clinical metrics heavily impacted the model's trajectory.
  - **LIME Bar Charts:** Highlights highly specific, localized patient decision rules calibrated against true training data bounds (`lime_training_background.csv`).
- **Context-Aware Medical AI Chatbot:** Uses LangChain with the `mistral-small-latest` model to provide patient-specific analysis of the clinical profile and XAI charts, running a rolling-window token compression algorithm to prevent rate limits.

---

## 📦 Project Architecture & Directory Layout

```text
heart_attack_prediction/
│
├── index.html                  # Frontend User Interface Dashboard
├── style.css                   # Custom responsive UI stylesheet
├── main.py                     # Core FastAPI backend, ML scoring & LLM pipeline
├── heart_disease_voting_ensemble.pkl # Persisted pre-trained voting model
├── lime_training_background.csv # Statistical sample matrix for accurate LIME rules
├── requirements.txt            # System dependency listing (Native Python)
└── .gitignore                  # Prevents tracking of large local environments (.venv, .env)
🛠️ Local Installation & Setup
1. Prerequisites
Ensure you have Python 3.11+ installed on your local computer.

2. Navigate to the Project
Open your terminal or PowerShell window and navigate to your workspace directory:

PowerShell
cd C:\Users\gajje\OneDrive\Desktop\pro2\heart_attack_prediction
3. Initialize & Activate the Virtual Environment
PowerShell
python -m venv .venv
# On Windows PowerShell:
.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1
4. Install Dependencies
PowerShell
python -m pip install --upgrade pip
python -m pip install -r requirements.txt
5. Configure Your Secret Environment Keys
Create a file named exactly .env in the root directory and add your variables:

Ini, TOML
MISTRAL_API_KEY=your_actual_mistral_api_key
PORT=8000
HOST=127.0.0.1
6. Run the Application Backend
PowerShell
python main.py
The server will initialize locally on http://127.0.0.1:8000. You can now launch index.html using a local server extension (like VS Code Live Server) to interact with the platform!

🌐 Production Cloud Deployment (Render Native Python)
This project is fully structured to deploy natively on Render without requiring Docker containers:

Backend Engine (Web Service): Create a Web Service on Render linking to your GitHub repository. Set the Runtime to Python 3, the Build Command to pip install -r requirements.txt, and the Start Command to uvicorn main:app --host 0.0.0.0 --port 10000. Add your MISTRAL_API_KEY in the Environment Variables section.

Frontend UI (Static Site): Create a Static Site service on Render using the same repository. Leave the build command blank and set the publish directory to . (the root).

CORS Alignment: Take the generated public live web domain from your Static Site service and append it inside the CORSMiddleware setup array block within your main.py script to authorize browser network handshakes.

⚖️ Clinical Disclaimer
This software application is a prototype demonstrating machine learning statistical predictive analysis and localized model interpretation (XAI). It is intended exclusively as an educational developer project. It is not a diagnostic medical tool, does not provide medical advice, and all generated insights must be cross-verified by a licensed healthcare professional or cardiologist.